                        <summary>
                            
                            <p>This inscription states that the temple, evidently the one dedicated to Brahmapurīśvara, along with the <hi rend="italic">maṇḍapa</hi> was constructed, for the welfare of <hi rend="bold">Aḻagiya-Pallavaṉ Kō-Nandipaṉmar,</hi> by <hi rend="bold">Villi Tiruvaṉ Tirikattarāyaṉ</hi> of the village.</p>						
                            
                            <p>The script in which this inscription is engraved may be assigned to the 13th century A.D.</p>						
                            
                            <p>The title Aḻagiya-Pallavaṉ, as pointed out in No. 259 above, is applied to the Kāḍava chiefs Kōpperuñjiṅgadēva I and II and the Nandi mentioned in the present record may be identified with Sundara (Tamil Aḻagiya) Nandipanmar mentioned as a <hi rend="italic">mudali</hi> of Nīlagaṅgaraiyar in a record of the 14th year of Kōpperuñjiṅgadēva from Vallam<note><hi rend="italic">S.I.I.</hi> Vol. IV, No. 634.</note> in the Chingleput district.</p>						
                            
                        </summary>
